rComments: You can say he is passionate and funny, he is not like those boring old-style professors. But the most important thing is not being funny for an instructor,  he really need to make his lecture more clear and organized instead of telling jokes
He is very enthusiastic. Though the material is a bit dull, his teaching is never boring.

Campbell is an AMAZING professor. He's young, passionate and knows what he's talking about. Problem sets are a must. Not a very math heavy course, more conceptual. The midterm was pretty hard but the final exam was really easy (probably because of the low class avg). Great guy. I would take this course again. Highly recommended!

If not the best, one of the best profs I've ever had. Very intellectually stimulating. All his exams are based on problems sets. You just need to divide each weeks problems sets into pieces. Textbook not required. Highly recommended.

Clearly one of the best professors at UTSC. His exams were very fair (I don't know what these guys below were talking about), lectures extremely interesting and intellectually stimulating. Easily one of the most fun Econ class I've taken at this school.

Prof.Campbell is one of the best economics professors at UTSC. The problem sets he posted were very helpful and the exams were tricky, but not killers. I would say if you studied the lecture notes and did all the problem sets, it's very easy to get a B+ or above in his class. At least he doesn't surprise you like most of the other profs at UTSC.

His English accent is so confusing and I did not like his teaching style at all. He explained the concept poorly and his office hours are useless.He did not give things on the past exam that is why I only got 60 in the midterm. I am so scared of finals.

He's a nice prof but his problem sets are too long and there is little to no idea what he's going to put on the exam. He posts past exams but this term his midterm was nothing like the past exams, the course material is easy if the person teaching could teach better
